
                               cimg
                     <file embedding in images>

features:
• embed any files into PNG, JPEG, BMP, or GIF images
• compress embedded data to save space
• extract embedded files from modified images
• preserves original image quality
• supports multiple file embedding

§ installation
git clone https://github.com/getjared/cimg.git
cd cimg
- gcc embed.c -o embed -lz
- gcc extract.c -o extract -lz

§ dependencies
• c compiler (gcc or clang)
• make
• zlib development libraries (zlib1g-dev on debian/ubuntu)

§ quick-start
embedding files:
    ./embed <input_image> <output_image> <file1_to_embed> [file2_to_embed ...]
    example: ./embed original.png modified.png secret.txt data.pdf

extracting files:
    ./extract <modified_image>
    example: ./extract modified.png

supported formats:
• PNG
• JPEG
• BMP
• GIF

§ extra
cimg is designed to be simple and efficient, allowing you to store files within image containers
while maintaining the image's visible quality. embedded files are automatically compressed to
minimize size impact. the program detects image formats automatically and handles them appropriately.

note: this tool is meant for legitimate file storage purposes. the modified images may be
larger than the originals due to the embedded data.

example usage:
1. embed multiple files:
   ./embed photo.jpg modified.jpg document.pdf notes.txt archive.zip

2. extract files later:
   ./extract modified.jpg
   > Extracted: document.pdf (156789 bytes)
   > Extracted: notes.txt (2045 bytes)
   > Extracted: archive.zip (1034567 bytes)
